description: This manzanita wasn't a very tall grower, and it was abundant. The bark was smooth and maroon/red, and the leaves were small, green, and pointed at the ends. It grew in the open, sunny areas of the Lower Montane Forest.

The herbaceous plant had thin, strong stalks and narrow, lightly shriveled blue-green leaves. The flowers were in bloom, showing off their light white colors. These were uncommon in this Lower Montane Forest.

The younger pine abounded with green pine needles and the characteristic huge cone of this species up on the main trunk. Most of these were older, so this one left an open, sunny spot in the canopy of the Lower Montane Forest.

This shrub was huge, and it was also fruiting, with the light green, grape-like fruits. On the branches, which were thin and very light, large thorns were present. The leaves were small and light green. It grew in the Lower Montane Forest.

These oaks were growing very abundantly, and their fresh leaves were brightly lit up by the sun's radiant light. The leaves were deeply lobed and deciduous. The bark wan't deeply grooved, and it was dark in color. These trees grew in mixed stands of oaks and conifers in the Lower Montane Forest.

The wildflower was very narrow and tall in structure, growing next to the pines. The small leaves were sage-like and blue-green, attached to the thin, long stems. At the tops of the stems were chains of bright red, beautiful tubular flowers. These were abundant in the Lower Montane Forest.
The plant was growing very low to the ground. The leaves were blue-green and compounded, strewn with large, light green sacs. It grew on the leaf litter covered floor of the Lower Montane Forest.

The deciduous shrub wasn't fit for poison oak, however the leaves were in bundles of three. Then, I saw the red, shiny berries which were characteristic of the Rhus genus. It grew in the Lower Montane Forest.

The perennial wildflower was very colorful, with the vase-shaped purple blooms. The leaves were narrow, green, thick, and lightly saw-toothed. It grew near low-growing shrubs in the Lower Montane Forest.

The wildflower was very narrow and tall in structure. The small leaves were sage-like and blue-green, attached to the thin, long stems. At the tops of the stems were bright, colorful chains of bright red, beautiful tubular flowers. These were abundant in the Lower Montane Forest.

The pine was large, snarly, and a common resident tree up at 5,500 feet. The bark was brown/red, deeply furrowed, and puzzle-piece like. A mesmerizing vanilla fragrance attracted me to the trunk, where that sap oozed in the bark. The cones weren't prickly when I picked them up from the ground. It grew in the Lower Montane Forest.

This young tree seemed to have a health issue with a fungus, because some of the bark appeared to be black. The leaves were evergreen, scaly and flattened. Its bark was fibrous and reddish-brown. It grew in the Lower Montane Forest.

The grass was a thick bunchgrass, with many slender green and dead blades. Though the stalks weren't present, the rest of the grass gave way to its identity. It grew near old stumps of long-lost logged pines in the Lower Montane Forest.

The seedling was very short, less than a foot tall, however its leaves were a hint to its parental history. They were deeply lobed and deciduous. These trees grew in mixed stands of oaks and conifers in the Lower Montane Forest, and they continued to germinate with seedlings like this one.

These oaks were growing very abundantly, even in the ravines. The leaves were deeply lobed and deciduous. The bark wan't deeply grooved, and it was dark in color. These trees grew in mixed stands of oaks and conifers in the Lower Montane Forest.
The plant was a low-growing deervetch, with tiny, hairy lobed leaves. The lotus-shaped flowers were tiny and yellow. These grew in open, mulched regions of the Lower Montane Forest.
This small wildflower grew among the dried pine needles and forbs. The lobed leaves were green with silvery fuzz. The flowers were rosy purple. It grew in the Lower Montane Forest.

The huge, dead tree had not fallen over yet, and it still stood proudly among the living trees. The bark was very deeply grooved, orange/red in color, and scented like a whiff of incense. The branches were bare and plentiful on the snag, which someday will fall and provide refuge to the critters of the Lower Montane Forest.

The small herbaceous plant had long, wide, blue-green leaves. Their undersides were a light, silvery gray. The leaves had three lobes, two small ones and a big one in the middle. It grew with ferns in the ravine corridor within the Lower Montane Forest.

The shrub wasn't a hardwood or even semiwoody plant. The leaves were wide, bright green, lobed into five leaflets. The stalks were very tall for a lupine, and the blooms were rose pink. It grew in the fresh vegetation within the Lower Montane Forest.

The small bird was scaling the tree like a woodpecker, going vertically while it searched under the bark for possible food. The head was white, and the cap was a thin line of black. The wings were blue-gray. It lived in the Lower Montane Forest.
The deciduous shrub formed thickets, and upon closer inspection the branches were thorny. The leaves were compound and slightly serrated. It grew in the ravine in the Lower Montane Forest.

The shrub had large, broadleaf foliage in clusters of about 5-6 leaves. The flowers were large, white, and lily-like. The buds were also pretty big, with a creamy-yellow color. It grew in the streambed within the Lower Montane Forest.

description: This wildflower was extremely small and tidy. The leaves were small, green, and triangular (not ovular). The pink flowers were tiny and had four main petals, each "petal" really being two split petals which appear to be one! It grew in the pine needle litter in the Lower Montane Forest.

This less abundant oak had many smooth branches, and the numerous trunks were packed closely together. The leaves were dark green, smooth, and had light undersides. The bark was rugged and dark brown. It grew in the Lower Montane Forest.

These oaks were growing very abundantly, and they served as wildlife nurseries for nearby wildlife, such as woodpeckers. The bright green leaves were deeply lobed and deciduous. These trees grew in the Lower Montane Forest.

The mother woodpecker was courageously caring for its offspring, seen in the nesting hole which was drilled into the oak trunk. The adult's head was white, and the wings and tail were black. It drilled heavily into the pine snag within the Lower Montane Forest.

The gall was thick, long, and similar in texture and color to the original bark of the tree. Instead of a colorful "apple" or "jewel", this one was merely a swollen stem, like a node in a way. it grew on the black oak in the Lower Montane Forest.

The oak had many smooth branches, and the numerous trunks were packed closely together. The leaves were dark green, smooth, and had light undersides. The bark was rugged and dark brown. It grew in the Lower Montane Forest.

The pine was large, snarly, and a common resident tree up at 5,500 feet. The bark was brown/red, deeply furrowed, and puzzle-piece like. The cones weren't prickly when I picked them up from the ground. It grew in the Lower Montane Forest.

The broadleaf tree was small, with several thin trunks, and many branches. The leaves were narrow, rounded, and dark green on the upper side and lighter green on the under side. It grew next to an intermittent stream in the Lower Montane Forest.

The small, herbaceous plant was low-growing, shade-loving, and fresh. The leaves were in bundles of three, but they were serrated and ovular unlike the infamous poison oak. These grew nearby the intermittent streambed in the Lower Montane Forest.

The pine tree was a very tall evergreen pine, with scaly, thin, gray bark and needles in bundles of five. The shape of the crown was unlike the Ponderosa and Jeffrey Pines, and the cones on the forest floor below this tree were long, not huge like the Coulter's. It grew high above the shrubs and granite boulders of the Lower Montane Forest.
The lichen was lime-green, very fibrous, and common on those dead branches. On the lichens, the hard, brown "eyes" were spotted as well. It latched on the dying snags in the Lower Montane Forest.

This shorter conifer wasn't fully mature, however the trunk, bark, and crown have all established themselves. The leaves were evergreen, scaly and flattened. Its bark was fibrous and reddish-brown. It grew in the Lower Montane Forest.

The wildflower was very narrow and tall in structure. The small leaves were sage-like and blue-green, attached to the thin, long stems. At the top of one of the stems was a chain of bright red, beautiful tubular flowers. These were abundant in the Lower Montane Forest.

These oaks were growing very abundantly, and their fresh leaves were seen from afar. They were deeply lobed and deciduous. The bark wan't deeply grooved, and it was dark in color. These trees grew in mixed stands of oaks and conifers in the Lower Montane Forest.

The dense concentration of mistletoe was hard to spot based on color alone, however the leaves were very different from the lobed, deciduous leaves of the host black oak. It was acting out as a parasite in the Lower Montane Forest, growing only in the oaks.

The pines were large individuals, with spreading, arched trunks and branches. The canopy abounded with green pine needles and the characteristic huge cones of this species. These trees appeared healthy and not diseased, they lived in the Lower Montane Forest.

The shrub was teeming with vase-shaped, rosy pink flowers, attracting insects from all around the woods! The thick leaves were light green and ovular with pointed ends. Inside the crown of leaves and flowers, the beautifully smooth, clay-red bark was seen, and I couldn't help but run my fingers along the smooth trunk of this spectacular native shrub. These grew with the pines and granite boulders in the Lower Montane Forest.

The raptor was like a gull, yet like a falcon at the same time. But its clear that this was beautiful indeed. Those slim, streamlined black wings and soft gray/white body made this bird stand out. It perched high on the willows in the Riparian Forest, nearby a shrike.

The kingbird was distant, so the features weren't too crystal clear. The chest was light gray, the belly was light yellow, and the head was all light gray, unlike the Cassin's which had the dark gray and white on the head. It perched on a dried snag stuck in the middle of a long-dry Freshwater Marsh.

This plant had tiny, thick, salt-repelling leaves and tiny, pink, five-petaled flowers. It grew in a small depression where water gathers during storms, likely contributing to the alkaline environment in this part of the Riparian Forest.

The plant had large, semi-woody stems and thin, long green leaves. The "messy" flowers were a brownish-white in color. It grew in dense stands, however these plants weren't the majority in the Riparian Forest ecosystem.

This broadleaf, deciduous tree was locally abundant on this stretch of land. The willow leaves were slim, glossy, and bright green on the upper and under sides. The bark was dark and deeply grooved. It grew in the thin, intact Riparian Forest strip.

These grasses were very thick, tubular, and long. The tops of the stems had flowering clusters. Thick stands of these were very common in the Freshwater Wetland.

The large, light-colored shrub was adapted for alkaline conditions. The branches were long and straight, and on them were rounded, ovular, light gray-green leaves. It was common in disturbed sites around the Freshwater Wetlands.

The three heron-like birds were flying high above the ground. However, upon closer inspection, the beak shape was thin and curved, equivalent of a curlew. One species pf ibis resides at this reserve, and today was the day I saw some of these, high above the Freshwater Wetlands.
The bird was a small passerine, with a black body and red/yellow streaks on the wings. It flew above a dry stretch of the Freshwater Wetland, then perching in some lonely rushes.

The passerine bird had gray-brown wings, a similarly colored head, a wagging tail, and a clay-colored belly. If flew while catching flying insects over the dried flats, then perched on small vegetation. It repeated this feeding behavior over and over in this dried Freshwater Wetland.

The large, light-colored shrub was adapted for alkaline conditions. The branches were long and straight, and on them were rounded, ovular, light gray-green leaves. It was common in disturbed sites around the Freshwater Wetlands.

These cattail grasses had thick fronds which were bright green and erect. There were two seeding "heads" on each frond, and these were thin and light brown. These grew very densely in the Freshwater Wetland.

This observation is for the mockingbird. It was very chatty, irritating, and a threat to the larger raven. In midair, it attacked the larger bird by swooping around the raven, then zooming down on the bird for an attack. The body coloration was mostly gray and white. This fierce behavior occurred in midair over the Freshwater Wetlands.

This observation is for the raven. The large, black bird had a thick, "square" tail, thick beak, and a croak-like call that was deep, unlike the crow. It wandered around the mockingbird too closely, and therefore the mockingbird released its rage on the raven, quickly shooing it off. This commotion occurred over the Freshwater Wetlands.
The egret was large and white. The legs were all black and the bill was orange. It perched on the slope of sedimentary soils bordering the Freshwater Wetland.

The flying bird was mixed in with the swallows, which were more graceful and glider-like in flight than this swift. This bird had stiffer flight movements. A large white band was seen on the belly's underside, a key indicator. It flew over the summer-dormant Freshwater Wetlands.
The egrets were large and white. The legs were all black and the bills were orange. They walked on the dirt road that rose next to the Freshwater Wetland.

description: The fern was locally abundant, their leaves and stems coming out of all the shady, cool landscapes in the area. The fronds were wide, bright green, and highly compound, characteristic of the Bracken ferns. It grew on the forest floor beneath the black oaks in the Lower Montane Forest.

The small passerine bird had gray wings, a thin tail, and a white cheek with a black stripe through the eye. It enjoyed the feeders deployed, it did indeed chow down! This species is the dominant member of these types of songbirds in this particular Lower Montane Forest.

These oaks were growing very abundantly, and their fresh leaves were seen from afar. They were deeply lobed and deciduous. These trees formed their own pure stand with brackerns in this Lower Montane Forest.
This seedling was very young, and still prone to threats with early age. The leaves were evergreen, scaly and flattened. Its bark had not fully developed yet. It grew in the Lower Montane Forest.
The older, snarly conifer was   a veteran, an elder in this forest. The leaves were evergreen, scaly and flattened. Its bark was fibrous and reddish-brown. It grew in the Lower Montane Forest.

The fern was locally abundant, their leaves and stems coming out of all the shady, cool landscapes in the area. The fronds were wide, bright green, and highly compound, characteristic of the Bracken ferns. It grew close to an intermittent stream with currants and willows in the Lower Montane Forest.

The currant was very green, and liked growing near the seasonal streambeds. The foliage was bright green, thin, and wide. The flowers were small and the buds were light pink. It grew in the moistest, shadiest regions of the Lower Montane Forest.

The young conifer was among far too many competing for survival in this forest. The leaves were evergreen, scaly and flattened. Its young bark was fibrous and reddish-brown. It grew in the Lower Montane Forest, on the border of a large clearing.

This 500+ year old pine is very special and iconic to the UC James Reserve, the trunk and resiliency alone of this tree is very worthy. The pine tree had the characteristic "puzzle-piece", reddish-brown bark. The needles were in bundles of three, and the pine cones were prickly on the outside. This one grew to enormous size in a clearing in the Lower Montane Forest.

This lotus plant is distant in the photo, however it was clear in person. It's in the fresh, green plant with compound leaves in the center. And it has one bloom (next to the middle of the image), a lotus-shaped flower that had white and yellow petals. This plant grew right next to the flowing intermittent stream in the Lower Montane Forest.

The fern was locally abundant, their leaves and stems coming out of all the shady, cool landscapes in the area. The fronds were wide, bright green, and highly compound, characteristic of the Bracken ferns. It grew next to an intermittent stream in the Lower Montane Forest.

The monkeyflower was a medium-sized shrub, with wide, serrated, green leaves. The yellow flowers had a little orange on the insides. The other species of yellow-flowering monkeyflowers around here don't match this species. It lived right next to the flowing intermittent stream in the Lower Montane Forest.

On the dusty dirt road, a moth caterpillar was found. The outside hairs were a light brown, and the center was dark black. It must have fallen from its host tree, somewhere in that Lower Montane Forest.

The wildflower was abundant in this forest, easily identified by the bunches of yellow blooms taking the shape of globes. These frequented richer soils with intermittent sun, an interesting observation. It made its home in the Lower Montane Forest.
The plant was a low-growing deervetch, with tiny, hairy lobed leaves. The lotus-shaped flowers were tiny and yellow. These grew in disturbed soils of the Lower Montane Forest.

This plant is very special, and seeing it brought me unspeakable joy! This one was drier and more limp than the rest, nevertheless it still stood. The colors, texture, shape, and visual beauty is unmistakable. This jewel grew with five other individuals in the Lower Montane Forest.

The wildflower was very narrow and tall in structure. The small leaves were sage-like and blue-green, attached to the thin, long stems. At the tops of the stems were chains of bright red, beautiful tubular flowers. These were abundant in the Lower Montane Forest.

The ceanothus was a large shrub-like tree, in full bloom. The white flowers were in numerous clusters throughout the shrub's crown. The leaves were rounded and green, the branches were stiff and straighter than many shrubs. It grew in a clearing of the Lower Montane Forest.
The young conifer was among dozens competing for survival in this forest. The leaves were evergreen, scaly and flattened. Its bark was fibrous and reddish-brown. It grew in the Lower Montane Forest.
The oak seedling was growing very nicely, with its strong, fresh new leaves. They were deeply lobed and deciduous. It grew under the conifers in this Lower Montane Forest.
